h3. Problem Definition
Unable to view changes made by users in Priorities such as Add, Edit and Delete (located under Issue Attributes)

h3. Suggested Solution
Allow [Audit Log|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver074/auditing-in-jira-applications-881684057.html] to record changes made to Priorities (or Issue Attributes as a whole) by users.

h3. Workaround

Currently, the only way to determine which users have made such changes is by running a grep command on all JIRA access logs using the keywords 'POST' and '_action_' (where _action_ is represented by JSP command in the URL that a user clicks to perform an action). An example would be:

jiraurl/secure/admin/*AddPriority*.jspa

where *AddPriority* represents a user adding a new Priority in the Issue Attributes.

As such, to search for all POST request to add new Priority, execute the following command in the {{[JIRA-INSTALL-DIR|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/JIRA+Installation+Directory]/logs/}}
{code}
grep 'POST' * | grep 'AddPriority'
{code}

A line from the output would look like this:

{panel:title=Example of output from grep command}
access_log.2017-08-10:10.60.3.225 963x9989x1 *admin* \[*10/Aug/2017:16:03:15 +0800*\] "*POST* /contextpath/secure/admin/AddPriority.jspa HTTP/1.1" 302 - 13 "http://jiraurl/contextpath/secure/admin/*AddPriority*.jspa" "Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X x_x_x) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/5x.x.x.xx Safari/537.36" "mb84ca"
{panel}

where the first bold word would be the user name, then followed by the date and time of the request, the POST request and the action done.

If you wish to narrow the output to request by a particular user _user_, run the following command:
{code}
grep 'POST' * | grep 'AddPriority' | grep user
{code}

(i) The lines outputted by grep only provides the information as stated above and does not give details as to what has been added, changed or deleted. Such details are not logged by the access logs.

(!) Please note that the above grep command shows all the request attempts in the access logs that have been made, successful or failed.

h4. Summary
Scroll option is not available when the *More* list (on issue view page) exceeds issue page

h4. Steps to reproduce
# Configure JIRA with additional plugins that add options in *More* list
In my instance, I installed Clone Plus for JIRA, JIRA to JIRA issue copy, Lucidchart Plugin
# Make sure *More* option has long list that exceeds view issue page
!page.png|thumbnail!
# Some options will not be visible

h4. Expected Result
User can scroll to view the hidden options

h4. Actual Result
Scrolling is not possible

h4. Suggestion
JIRA should have scrolling option within the *More* list

h4.Workaround
Add the following to Jira's [Announcement Banner|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver075/configuring-an-announcement-banner-935390981.html]:
{code}
<style type="text/css">
div#opsbar-operations_more_drop {
    overflow: scroll;
    height: 300px;
}

div#opsbar-operations_more_drop::before {
    content: "This menu is scrollable";
    text-align: center;
    font-style: italic;
    display: block;
    color: navy;
    font-weight: bold;
    margin-top: 2px;
}
</style>
{code}

If the menu on the Issues in Epic is affected use this :
{code}
<style type="text/css">

div#actions_10401_drop {
    overflow: scroll;
    height: 600px;
}

div#actions_10401_drop::before {
    content: "This menu is scrollable";
    text-align: center;
    font-style: italic;
    display: block;
    color: navy;
    font-weight: bold;
    margin-top: 2px;
}

</style>
{code}

(!) The Announcements banner is not checked for validity - pages can break if invalid HTML is inserted into the announcement banner. [This KB article|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/jira-pages-go-hidden-or-blank-after-adding-an-announcement-banner-396298891.html] has steps to remove a faulty banner, should there be a mistake.

h3. Summary
In [Skipping major versions when upgrading JIRA applications|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver073/skipping-major-versions-when-upgrading-jira-applications-861253103.html], we mentioned that :
* {quote}If you plan to upgrade from JIRA and JIRA Agile *less* than 6.4.x and 6.3.5 respectively, you must upgrade to JIRA Software 7.0 as an interim version before upgrading further.{quote}
which is not coherent with the information provided in [JIRA Software upgrade notes|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftware/jira-software-7-3-x-upgrade-notes-861251109.html] :
{quote}Upgrading from a version earlier than 7.0 - You must upgrade to JIRA Software 7.0 first, before upgrading to JIRA Software 7.3.{quote}
* Same for JIRA Service Desk {quote}If you plan to upgrade from JIRA and JIRA Service Desk *less* than 6.4x and 2.5.x respectively, you must upgrade to JIRA Service Desk 3.0 as an interim version before upgrading further.{quote}
which is also a misleading information according to [JIRA Service Desk upgrade notes|https://confluence.atlassian.com/servicedesk/jira-service-desk-3-3-x-upgrade-notes-861251112.html].

h3. Expected Results
Both JIRA Service Desk and Software need to be first upgraded to 3.0.0 and 7.0.0 respectively if user has/had installed JIRA Service Desk and Agile plugin on their pre-7 instance.

h3. Summary
When using an attribute that doesn't have a unique constraint as the username attribute in JIRA, such as {{mail}}, you may face a situation where you have two users with equal usernames.

h3. Expected Behavior
Refuse to sync a duplicated user and throw an error message.

h3. Actual Behavior
JIRA makes a mess:
* A new user is created with a {{#<number>}} appended to it;
* Some part of the code tries to handle that as a user rename, therefore altering the reference on {{app_user}};
* Both users will end up unable to log in;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Connect JIRA to an external LDAP directory;
# Set the username attribute to {{mail}};
# Create a user with any e-mail address;
# Synchronize the directory with JIRA;
# Create a new user in the external directory with the same e-mail address as the one on step 3;
# Synchronize the directory again;
# Note the below errors in the logs:
{noformat:borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
2017-07-05 14:49:12,210 Caesium-1-2 ERROR anonymous     [c.atlassian.scheduler.JobRunnerResponse] Unable to synchronise directory
com.atlassian.jira.exception.DataAccessException: org.ofbiz.core.entity.GenericEntityException: while updating: [GenericEntity:User][lastName,Doe][lowerDisplayName,john doe][displayName,John Doe][lowerLastName,doe][active,0][externalId,xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx][updatedDate,2017-07-05 14:49:12.067][userName,john@doe.com][lowerEmailAddress,john@doe.com][firstName,John][emailAddress,john@doe.com][lowerUserName,john@doe.com][createdDate,2016-06-17 19:34:31.885][credential,nopass][deletedExternally,null][directoryId,10300][lowerFirstName,john][id,102084] (SQL Exception while executing the following:UPDATE public.cwd_user SET directory_id=?, user_name=?, lower_user_name=?, active=?, created_date=?, updated_date=?, first_name=?, lower_first_name=?, last_name=?, lower_last_name=?, display_name=?, lower_display_name=?, email_address=?, lower_email_address=?, CREDENTIAL=?, deleted_externally=?, EXTERNAL_ID=? WHERE ID=? (ERROR: duplicate key value violates unique constraint "uk_user_name_dir_id"
  Detail: Key (lower_user_name, directory_id)=(john@doe.com, 10300) already exists.))
{noformat}
{noformat:borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
